ğŸ”§ A Day in the Life of a DevOps Engineer ğŸ› ï¸

ğŸ•˜ Morning Stand-Up & Planning
My day begins with a stand-up meeting to review tasks, discuss blockers, and set priorities. I then check the status of CI/CD pipelines and address any issues from the previous day.
ğŸ” Monitoring Infrastructure
Next, I monitor system health using tools like Prometheus and Grafana, addressing any anomalies or alerts from tools such as Splunk. This helps in maintaining optimal performance and security.
âš™ï¸ CI/CD Pipeline Management
Mid-morning is dedicated to optimizing and troubleshooting our CI/CD pipelines with Jenkins or GitLab. I fix build issues and work with developers on automation improvements.
ğŸš€ Infrastructure as Code (IaC)
I then focus on IaC tasks, using Terraform or CloudFormation to manage cloud resources and Docker for containerization. This involves scripting and scaling infrastructure as needed.
ğŸ›¡ï¸ Security & Code Review
Security is key, so I review code for vulnerabilities with SonarQube and manage secrets with HashiCorp Vault. I also handle access management and security audits.
ğŸ”„ Troubleshooting & Issue Resolution
Throughout the day, I address any production issues, analyze logs, and collaborate with the dev team to resolve problems swiftly.
ğŸ¤ Collaboration & Knowledge Sharing
Later, I participate in cross-team meetings, share updates, and document improvements. Collaboration helps us stay aligned and enhance our processes.
ğŸ“š Learning & Experimentation
I allocate time to explore new tools and techniques, whether it's a Kubernetes feature or an improved deployment strategy, to stay current and innovative.
ğŸ“… End of Day Review
I wrap up by reviewing progress, updating tasks in Jira, and preparing for the next dayâ€™s stand-up.
ğŸ”‘ Key Takeaway:
As a DevOps Engineer, my day revolves around monitoring, automation, troubleshooting, and collaboration to keep our systems stable, secure, and evolving.

==================================================================================================================================================================
Production Checklist for any major deployment/upgrade: 

âœ… Configure liveness & readiness probe for the application
âœ… Prepare a backup & restore strategy
âœ… Make sure the application is deployed as a set of replicas (Deployment/Daemon-set)
âœ… Consider using anti-affinity rules for the deployment to place pods/containers evenly across the cluster
âœ… Set Pod disruption budgets
âœ… Set memory limits and requests for all containers
âœ… Disable CPU limits â€” unless you have a good use case
âœ… Set an appropriate Quality of Service (QoS) for Pods
âœ… Use the Horizontal Pod Autoscaler for apps with variable usage patterns
âœ… Externalise all configuration
âœ… Define appropriate LimitRange & ResourceQuota on Namespaces for apps
âœ… Enable Network Policies
âœ… Structured Logging & monitoring should be in-place
âœ… Pod Security Policies (PSA, OPA, GateKeeper) should be in-place

