Default Ports:

In the world of DevOps and Networking, ports are essential for communication between services and servers. Each service or protocol uses a specific port to handle requests. Here are some commonly used default ports that every DevOps professional should know:

Port 22 - SSH: For secure remote login and file transfers.
Port 80 - HTTP: Standard port for unencrypted web traffic.
Port 443 - HTTPS: Secure, encrypted web traffic.
Port 3000 - Grafana: Used for monitoring and dashboards.
Port 9090 - Prometheus: For collecting metrics and monitoring.
Port 25 - SMTP: For sending emails.
Port 53 - DNS: Resolves domain names to IP addresses.
Port 3306 - MySQL: Default port for MySQL databases.
Port 6379 - Redis: Fast in-memory data storage (caching).
Port 5601 - Kibana: For visualizing data from Elasticsearch.
Port 9100 - Node Exporter: Collects hardware and OS metrics for Prometheus.
Port 3100 - Loki: Log aggregation system for storing and querying logs.
Port 9200 - Elasticsearch: Used for full-text search and log analytics.
Port 8080 - Tomcat: Default HTTP port for Apache Tomcat server.
Port 5432 - PostgreSQL: Default port for PostgreSQL database connections.

==================================================================================================================================================================
ğŸš€ Cloud & DevOps Interview Questions (Explained Simply!)

ğŸ”¹ Docker Basics
1ï¸âƒ£ What is Docker, and how does it work?

Docker is a tool that packages your application and everything it needs (like libraries) into a container. These containers can run the same way on any system, ensuring your app works everywhere.

2ï¸âƒ£ How do containers differ from virtual machines?

Containers: Lightweight, share the systemâ€™s OS, and start quickly.
Virtual Machines: Heavier because they include their own OS, making them slower to start and use more resources.

3ï¸âƒ£ What is Docker Compose?

Itâ€™s a tool to run apps with multiple containers (e.g., a web app with a database). You define everything in one file, and with a single command, Docker Compose sets up the entire environment for you.

ğŸ”¹ Kubernetes Concepts
4ï¸âƒ£ What is Kubernetes, and why is it used?

Kubernetes (K8s) is like a manager for your containers. It handles where and how containers run, makes sure they restart if they fail, balances traffic, and even scales them up or down automatically.

5ï¸âƒ£ How do you deploy a Kubernetes cluster?

You need tools like kubectl and a container runtime (e.g., Docker). Then, you create a cluster, add worker nodes, and deploy your application using YAML files.

6ï¸âƒ£ What are Kubernetes Pods?

A pod is the smallest unit in Kubernetes. Think of it as a group that holds one or more containers that work together. They share the same network and storage.

ğŸ”¹ Advanced Kubernetes
7ï¸âƒ£ How do you manage Kubernetes secrets?

Kubernetes Secrets store sensitive data like passwords securely. You create a secret, and your application accesses it without exposing it to the public.

8ï¸âƒ£ What are Kubernetes Ingress and Services?

Service: Helps different parts of your app (or users) connect to your containers.
Ingress: Handles HTTP/HTTPS traffic and routes it to the right container, like directing website visitors to the correct page.

9ï¸âƒ£ How do you monitor and scale a Kubernetes cluster?

Monitor: Use tools like Prometheus and Grafana to check how your app and cluster are performing.
Scale: Add more containers (pods) manually or automatically if the app gets busy.

ğŸ”Ÿ What is a service mesh in Kubernetes?
A service mesh (e.g., Istio) makes communication between containers easy, secure, and manageable. It handles traffic control and encrypts data between services without needing to change your code.

